section.p:
In this section, we consider a mathematical tool called a matrix (plural: matrices) that has wide application in mathematics, business, science, and engineering. A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers or entries. These entries are ordinarily displayed in rows and columns, and the entire matrix is enclosed in brackets or parentheses. Thus,
\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 2\amp 3 \\ 4 \amp5 \amp6 \\ 7 \amp8\amp 9 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}2\amp −1\amp 3 \\4\amp 0\amp 2 \end{bmatrix}, \text{ and } \begin{bmatrix} 4\\5\\6 \end{bmatrix}
are matrices. A matrix of order, or dimension, n\times m (read "n by m") has n (horizontal) rows and m (vertical) columns. The matrices above are 3\times 3, 2\times 3, and 3\times 1, respectively. The first matrix—in which the number of rows is equal to the number of columns—is an example of a square matrix.
